Hiii birth workers out there who aren’t trans, I just want to bring it to your attention that this season of anti-trans legislation has all of us scared, but the impact this is having on trans parents and trans people in the process of building their families is specific and horrible. We’re facing a culture war where the main oppressive rhetoric is that it’s not safe for children to be around us, see us, or even know we exist. And as we start seeing headlines about sperm donors receiving parental rights while queer non-gestational parents’ custody is stripped away, the vision of our futures are terrifying and heartbreaking. All of this is to say that it’s more important than ever before to be ready to support the trans parents and people in your community. If you need help getting ready, I’m here for you. Workshops are this week, don’t miss your chance to learn with this awesome cohort! 
.
.
.
.
#GenderAffirming #TransParents #TransFamily #SupportTransParents #ProtectTransFamilies #MossTheDoula #TransDoula #TransBirth #TransBirthWorker

In the midst of this nightmare moment of anti-trans sentiment and legislation, spring is springing, and I hope that means that direct action will start blooming too. It feels gross to be hocking tshirts right now, but if something to wear to a protest, to go talk to your representatives, or just show your support at the farmers market is something you need, these tshirts are here and available. The money I make on these sales supports my ability to provide the support services I offer for free in the form of things like my Trans & Gestating Support Group, the support I offer on a sliding scale like all of my full spectrum birth & transition work with clients, and my ability to continue working on and someday finish this book project which will be a postpartum resource for trans & queer families.
.
.
.
.
#ProtectTransFamilies #ProtectTransHealth #ProtectTransHealthcare #Trans #TransDoula #Transgender #TransBirth #TransParents #MossTheDoula

Speaking at College of Charleston last week was such a landmark experience in my journey of working to support trans and queer people building their families and interacting with the perinatal health world. I’m so grateful to have finally gotten to spend time with Cristina aka Dr. D in person, and have had the chance meet so many of their students. Cristina, it’s so clear that your presence in these young peoples lives has such an incredible impact, and they’re living for the ideas and conversations you’re sharing with them. So honored to be part of this world you’re building with them. Thank you so much to Naomi who works so hard to provide space for the trans and queer students of CofC. And thank you to my amazing partner and roadie Stel who graciously listened to me talk pretty much all day every day all week, and documented all of this. Aaaand thank you to my sweet friends who were the perfect place to land for a tiny beach trip afterward, I love you all so much!

I was gifted this amazing piece of queer conception history by my neighbor Pat, and I am so excited to add it to my collection. This is a small book called “Woman Controlled Conception” published by  the Womanshare collective, a community of lesbians living on collective land in Oregon, in 1979. Reading through this collection of stories of people conceiving on their own at a time when there was so little precedent and infrastructure to rely on in the process is very perspective-giving, and has me feeling so grateful for the generations of queers who came before us and for my incredible community of trans and queer people in this work of education and support for people trying to conceive. Looking at this book, it’s wild to think about what in this process has changed so much (support and accessible information), and what has pretty much not changed at all (waking body temp tracking!). 
.
.
.
#QueerTTC #QueerArchives #LesbianHistory #QueerHistory #QueerFamilies #QueerFamilyBuilding

Another new printable PDF just dropped on my Patreon! This time, it’s all about positioning and helping a baby get into the most advantageous position for birth. This handy two-pager lays out in words and images what the OP and OA positions are, and what movements we can do during late pregnancy and throughout labor to help the baby get into the OA position, to hopefully help labor go more smoothly. Patrons at all levels get access to this resource, and many more I’ve got planned coming in the next few months! Link in bio/ Patreon.com/mossthedoula
.

Sitting in my office reminiscing about my June adventures. Help me get my birth worker brain back! What trans affirming perinatal resources do you want to see here and on Patreon?

New resource up now on Patreon! This one’s a labor positions cheat sheet- it lays out 3 pages of commonly helpful labor positions with quick and easy info about when/why they might be helpful. It includes quick reference symbols to help you quickly identify positions that might be good for things like relieving back pain, helping the baby descend, helping an OP baby rotate, and pushing. Available for download now on my Patreon for patrons at all levels!

Y’all! I’m excited to be able to update you that I’ve finished all of the interviews for this book project I’m working on! For those of you who are just tuning in, I’m working on writing a trans & queer guide to postpartum. As someone who’s way into this is supporting people in their postpartum times, and not having experienced it myself, I wanted to interview many trans & queer people who have experienced postpartum and make this book a conduit for parents to tell their stories and speak to expecting parents (and the people who plan to support them) directly. I’m so grateful to everyone who interviewed and shared their stories and experiences with me! Now that I’ve completed these interviews with 9 different parents, I have so much work to do to transcript, edit the transcripts, organize the stories, and write the into the gaps between them. I’m finding that this work is going to take more time than I can afford to take away from client and consulting work, so I’m asking for support from those of y’all out there who are invested in this book’s eventual existence and have a little bit of cash to spare! You can support this work by subscribing to my Patreon (link in bio) at any level (from $3 to $50/month), or buying tshirts and tote bags from my “protect trans families/health” merch store! (Also link in bio). I can’t wait to share these stories with y’all!

Really appreciating @epliphotography today. Their project, Home//made, documenting trans, butch, and gnc parents and families is something I often come back to when thinking about why I do this work. And I love that now I can do that by looking through this beautiful book! Check out their site and shop for this book and prints!

Reproductive justice is the foundation of why I do this work. Reproductive justice means the human right to control if, when, where, and how we have and parent children and grow our families. Right now in Gaza, around 50,000 people are currently pregnant, around 5500 of them due to give birth this month. Because of xsraeli apartheid, and the thousands of bombs still being dropped on the palestinian people of Gaza, these people have basically no access to prenatal or birth care, anesthesia for c sections, NICU care, or postpartum care. If someone in this situation survives giving birth under these conditions, they will be experiencing postpartum displaced, with their home likely destroyed. They will have extremely limited access to water and food. They will be living through postpartum likely unhoused and under constant fear of being murdered by bombs. If a parent and their baby survive postpartum under these conditions, they will be raising their children under occupation, in constant fear that their child will be killed, like the thousands of children of Gaza that have been murdered in the past week. This is why those of us who fight for reproductive justice can not tolerate violent settler colonialism. There are innumerable reasons to fight for the freedom of Palestine, but as birth workers and people who believe in reproductive justice, we can not reasonably turn away. We must demand freedom for Palestine. 🍉

Today is day 45 of the escalated and continued genocide being waged against Palestine by the settler colonial state of Israel. Over 11,000 Palestinian people have been murdered since October 7, including 5,000 children, and more lives are stolen every day. As trans care workers who are deeply committed to liberation for all people,we want to be unequivocally clear: we are in solidarity with Palestine. 

Today, on Trans Day of Remembrance, we uplift the beautiful lives of the queer and trans Palestinians who have been murdered by the settler colony of Israel for the past 75 years. We honor their spirits, carry them in our hearts, and vow to fight for an end to imperialism, white supremacy, and oppression in their memories.

We join with the Palestinian and Jewish people who are working – often, together – to lead continued resistance to the Israeli apartheid state. We decry the relentless attempts to erase this ongoing solidarity, and uplift the truth of our collective power. 

We believe in a world where Palestine is free; where Arab people are safe and islamophobia and the dehumanization of Arab people are no more; where Jewish people are safe and anti-Semitism is a relic of the past; where Sudan, Congo, and Haiti are liberated and the chains of Western imperialism have been broken; where queer people are celebrated; where our current systems of extraction and violence have been replaced with systems of community care. On this sacred day of mourning and celebrating trans lives lost, we hold our vision for a better world steady, as we work together to build it ourselves. 

#TDOR #TransDayOfRemembrance #CeaseFireNow #FreePalestine #LetGazaLive
